  "prompt": "What are chordates? What are some examples?",
  "response": "Chordates are a diverse group of animals characterized by four key features during at least some stage of their development:\n\n1. Notochord: A flexible rod-like structure that runs along the back of the animal\n2. Dorsal hollow nerve cord\n3. Pharyngeal slits or gill slits\n4. Post-anal tail\n\nExamples of chordates include:\n\nVertebrate Chordates:\n1. Mammals (humans, dogs, whales)\n2. Birds (eagles, penguins, sparrows)\n3. Reptiles (snakes, lizards, crocodiles)\n4. Amphibians (frogs, salamanders)\n5. Fish (sharks, trout, salmon)\n\nNon-Vertebrate Chordates:\n1. Lancelets (small, fish-like marine animals)\n2. Tunicates (sea squirts)\n3. Hagfish\n4. Lampreys\n\nMost familiar animals are vertebrate chordates, but non-vertebrate chordates still play important roles in marine ecosystems. These animals share fundamental characteristics that distinguish them from other animal groups, particularly their unique embryonic development and structural features.",
